# PRD First Draft

You are writing a first-draft PRD that a PM will use as a working document — not a throwaway. The PRD must be specific: measurable success metrics, clear non-goals, and user stories in "as a [role], I want [goal] so that [outcome]" format. Total length 400–600 words.

Structure the output exactly into these sections. Use the section headers as written below.

1. PROBLEM (what and why) — 2–4 sentences. What is the problem, who has it, and why does it matter now? Use problem_statement; do not genericize.

2. GOALS (measurable) — 3–5 bullet goals. Each must be measurable or testable (e.g. "Reduce time to produce report pack by 50% for users with 10+ reports," "Support bulk export of up to 25 reports in one action"). No vague goals like "improve user satisfaction."

3. NON-GOALS (explicit) — 2–4 bullets. What we are explicitly not doing in this scope (e.g. "No combined single PDF in v1," "No new report types," "No API-only solution"). Prevents scope creep.

4. USER STORIES (3–5 in "as a … I want … so that …" format) — Cover the main flows. Use target_user. Examples: "As an ops lead, I want to select multiple reports and export them to PDF in one action so that I can prepare the monthly board pack in under 10 minutes."

5. SUCCESS METRICS — 2–4 specific metrics we will track (e.g. "Adoption: % of accounts with 10+ reports that use bulk export in first 90 days," "Time: survey or support follow-up on time saved"). Tie to success_definition. No vague "engagement" or "satisfaction" without definition.

6. OPEN QUESTIONS — 3–5 questions the PM or team needs to resolve (e.g. "Max reports per bulk export?"," "Single combined PDF vs. zip of PDFs?"). Make them answerable and actionable.

7. OUT OF SCOPE — 1–3 items that are explicitly out of scope for this PRD (can overlap with non-goals; be brief). E.g. "API for bulk export," "Scheduled bulk export."

Use the optional inputs (constraints, related_features, stakeholders, timeline_pressure) where relevant. No placeholders; write so the PM can edit and socialize.


## Context Needed
Required: problem_statement, target_user, success_definition
Optional: constraints (None specified), related_features (None specified), stakeholders (To be confirmed), timeline_pressure (None)

## Rules
- Output must follow the seven section headers exactly.
- Success metrics must be specific and measurable; no vague "engagement" or "satisfaction."
- 400–600 words. PM uses this as a working document.


## Good Output Looks Like
PROBLEM (what and why)
Customers with 10+ reports cannot efficiently export and share them for board or leadership reviews. They currently open each report and export to PDF manually, which is error-prone and time-consuming. We have had 3+ requests in 6 months and one enterprise customer cited this as a renewal concern. The problem matters now because we are expanding in enterprise and board/report-pack workflows are a common ask.

GOALS (measurable)
- Enable users to select and export multiple reports to PDF in one action (v1: up to 25 reports).
- Reduce time to produce a report pack by at least 50% for users with 10+ reports (measured via survey or time-tracking in follow-up).
- Decrease support tickets and NPS comments related to "export" or "report pack" within 6 months of launch.
- Ship by end of Q2 to support board reporting season and the customer who asked for it by June.

NON-GOALS (explicit)
- We are not building a single combined PDF in v1; output is multiple PDFs (or zip). Combined PDF may be a follow-up.
- We are not adding new report types or changing the report engine; we use the existing PDF pipeline.
- We are not building API-only bulk export in this PRD; UI-first.

USER STORIES
- As an ops lead, I want to select multiple reports and export them to PDF in one action so that I can prepare the monthly board pack in under 10 minutes.
- As an ops lead, I want to see progress and completion when exporting many reports so that I know the job is running and when it is done.
- As an admin, I want to ensure bulk export respects existing permissions so that users cannot export reports they should not see.
- As an ops lead, I want to download the exported files (zip or individual PDFs) so that I can attach or share them in email or other tools.

SUCCESS METRICS
- Adoption: % of accounts with 10+ reports that use bulk export at least once in the first 90 days after launch. Target: 20% of such accounts.
- Time: Follow-up survey or support check — "How much time do you save per report pack?" Target: 50%+ reduction for users with 10+ reports.
- Support/NPS: Count of tickets and NPS comments mentioning "export" or "report pack" in the 6 months post-launch vs. prior 6 months. Target: decrease.

OPEN QUESTIONS
- Max number of reports per bulk export in v1 (25 proposed; confirm with eng for performance).
- Single combined PDF vs. zip of PDFs — which do we ship first? Customer said "share with board" — does that mean one doc or a folder?
- Permissions: same as single report export, or do we need a new "bulk export" permission?
- Error handling: if one report fails, do we fail all or return partial success?

OUT OF SCOPE
- API-only bulk export (UI-first in this PRD).
- Scheduled bulk export (separate roadmap item).
- New report types or report engine changes.

